<hr />
  <dl style="margin-left: 2 em">
  <a name="snakeheadcross"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SNAKEHEAD CROSS</dt>
  <dd>A term that may be used for that variation of a cross moline where the 
  curved pieces at the ends are each formed by the head of a snake � a cross gringol�e � but see 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvcr.html#crossmoline">cross moline</a>&rsquo; 
  (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvcq.html#cross">cross 2)</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4417.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4417.gif" alt="[Sittard, NL]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1541.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1541.gif" alt="[Schinnen, NL]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1542.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1542.gif" alt="[Munstergeleen, NL]" border="0" height="108"></a><br />
  <em>Former Flag of <a href="nl-li_si.html#si">Sittard</a>, The Netherlands (fotw); 
  Flag of <a href="nl-li-sc.html">Schinnen</a>, The Netherlands (fotw); 
  Flag of <a href="nl-li-st.html#mg">Munstergeleen</a>, The Netherlands (fotw)
  <p>Please note that a snakehead-cross � a cross gringol�e - now appears to be largely 
  (but not exclusively) limited to Dutch usage (as is illustrated below).</em>
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4479.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4479.gif" alt="[snakehead cross]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <br>
  <em>Flag of <a href="fr-35-mm.html">Montfort-sur-Meu</a>, France (fotw)</em>
  </dd>

  <hr />
  <a name="solardisk"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SOLAR DISC (or DISK)</dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvd3.html#disc">disc</a>&rsquo;  
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1286.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1286.gif" alt="[Yakutia]" border="0" height="108"></a><br />
  <em>Flag of <a href="ru-14.html">Yakutia</a>, Russian Federation (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="solarsign"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SOLAR SIGN (or EMBLEM)</dt>
  <dd>In largely East European and West Asian usage, a stylized emblem (of varying design) that 
  symbolizes an ancient or ancestral veneration of the sun &ndash; but see note below (also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-e.html#emblem">emblem 1)</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d992.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d992.gif" alt="[Ingushetia]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3408.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3408.gif" alt="[Khakass people]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4490.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4490.gif" alt="[solar sign]" border="0" height="108"></a><br />
  <em>Flag of <a href="ru-06.html">Ingushetia</a>, Russia (fotw); Flag of the 
  <a href="ru-19.html#unof">Khakass people</a> (fotw); 
  Flag of <a href="ru-06-na.html">Nazranovsky District</a>, Russia (fotw)
  <p>
  Please note that the solar sign is not a stylized representation of the sun itself, but refers rather to its veneration or worship &ndash; see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs8.html#sunemblem">sun emblem</a>&rsquo;. 
  </em>    </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="sonsinserviceflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SONS OF SERVICE FLAG</dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs2.html#serviceflag">service flag 4)</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d650.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d650.gif" alt="single star service pennant" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d650a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d650a.gif" alt="two star service pennant" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d650b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d650b.gif" alt="single gold star/two blue star service pennant" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d650c.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d650c.gif" alt="Canadian service pennant" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Sons in Service Flags US (fotw); Canada (CS)</em>
  </dd>

  <hr /><a name="southerncross"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SOUTHERN CROSS </dt>
  <dd>1) A stylized representation of the constellation Crux Australis, and used 
  as a symbol on flags in the Southern Hemisphere &ndash; as on those of, for example, 
  <a href="au.html">Australia</a>, <a href="nz.html">New Zealand</a> and Samoa. </dd>
  <dd>2) A colloquial name for the saltire as used by the Confederate States of 
  America on its battle flag, second naval jack and later national flags (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb3.html#battleflag">battle flag 1)</a>&rsquo; 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs6.html#stainlessbanner">stainless banner</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs6.html#starsandbars">stars and bars</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3043.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3043.gif" alt="[Southern Crosses]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d303.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d303.gif" alt="[Southern Crosses]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d303a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d303a.gif" alt="[Southern Crosses]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <br />
  <em>Civil Ensign of <a href="nz_ens.html#cen">New Zealand</a> (fotw); 
  National Flag of <a href="ws.html">Samoa</a> (fotw); 
  <a href="us-csan.html#jack">Second Naval Jack</a> 1863-1865, 
  CSA (fotw) </em>
  </dd>
  <hr /><a name="southeast"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SOUTH-EAST DIAGONAL</dt>
  <dd>A diagonal stripe that runs from the lower hoist to the upper fly whose corners may (or may not) 
  touch the corners of the flag, but whose width is contained within the length of the flag at the hoist 
  and its width at the fly (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt!dv-9.html">Appendix XI</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dva8.html#ascendingdiag">ascending diagonal</a>&rsquo;,
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvd1.html#descendingdiag">descending diagonal</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-e.html#ewdiagonal">east-west diagonal</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvn2.html#northeast">north-east diagonal</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvn2.html#northsouth">north-south diagonal</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs5.html#southnorth">south-north diagonal</a>&rsquo;,
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-w.html#westnorth">west-north diagonal</a>&rsquo;,
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-w.html#westeast">west-east diagonal</a>&rsquo;,
  and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-w.html#westsouth">west-south diagonal</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2061.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2061.gif" alt="Motuca, Brazil" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d877.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d877.gif" alt="Bestin, Czechia" border="0" height="108"  /></a><br/>
  <em>Flag of <a href="br-sp361.html">Motuca</a>, Brazil (fotw); Flag of 
  <a href="cz-be-bs.html">B&#283;�t�n</a>, Czechia (fotw)<p>Please note that this term, whilst an extension of those existing and 
  established, has been introduced by the editors.</p></em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="southnorth"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SOUTH-NORTH DIAGONAL </dt>
  <dd>A diagonal stripe that runs from the lower hoist to the upper fly whose 
  corners may or may not touch the corners of the flag but whose width is 
  entirely contained within the length of the flag &ndash; an enhanced bend sinister 
  - see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb5.html#bend">bend</a>&rsquo; and &lsquo;<a href="vxt!dv-9.html">Appendix IX</a>&rsquo; 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dva8.html#ascendingdiag">ascending diagonal</a>&rsquo;,
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvd1.html#descendingdiag">descending diagonal</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-e.html#ewdiagonal">east-west diagonal</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvn2.html#northeast">north-east diagonal</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvn2.html#northsouth">north-south diagonal</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs5.html#southeast">south-east diagonal</a>&rsquo;,
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-w.html#westeast">west-east diagonal</a>&rsquo;,
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-w.html#westnorth">west-north diagonal</a>&rsquo;,
  and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-w.html#westsouth">west-south diagonal</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2522.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2522.gif" alt="Congo" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2562.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2562.gif" alt="Amhara, Ethiopia" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <br />
  <em>National Flag of The <a href="cf.html">Congo</a> (fotw); 
  Flag of <a href="et-am.html">Amhara</a>, Ethiopia (fotw)</em><hr /><a name="souvenirflags"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SOUVENIR FLAGS (or PENNANTS)</dt>
  <dd>1) Flags sold as a memento of those locales which do have an official design (see also �<a href="vxt-dvs8.html#subnationalflag">sub-national flag</a>�).</dd>
	  <dd>2) A generic term for flags or pennants exchanged during sporting matches by the captains 
  of the contending teams � a flag exchange (see also '<a href="vxt-dvc4.html#clubpennant">club pennant</a>', 
  &lsquo;<a href="#sportsflag">sports flag 1)</a>&rsquo; and &lsquo;<a href="#sportsflag">sports flag 2)</a>&rsquo;).</dd>
  <dd>3) Burgees presented to a club by visiting yachts, or collected by such visitors for display at 
  their home port (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb8.html#burgee">burgee 1)</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc4.html#clubpennant">club pennant</a>&rsquo;).</dd>
  <dd>4) See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb7.html#bragflags">brag flags</a>&rsquo;.</dd>
  <dd>5) See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc6.html#commerorativeflag">commemorative flag</a>&rsquo;.</dd>
  <dd>6) Small flags or pennants sold (or issued) to school children and/or street-lining 
  spectators for the purpose of waving at visiting dignitaries - usually in honour of a specific 
  event (see also '<a href="vxt-dv-h.html#handwaver">handwaver</a>').
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3657.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3657.gif" alt="souvenir flag" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3658.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3658.gif" alt="souvenir flag" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3659.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3659.gif" alt="souvenir flag" border="0" height="108"></a><br>
  <em>Souvenir Flag of the <a href="mx-!t.html">Distrito Federal</a>, Mexico (fotw); Flag of 
  <a href="gb-e@bfc.html">Bradford City FC</a>, UK (fotw); Burgee of the 
  <a href="us~ycaae.html">Aeolian Yacht Club</a>, US (fotw) 
  </em> 
  <p><em>Please note however, it is strongly suggested that the types of 
  flag given in 2) above are better defined by their type and/or circumstances of presentation, and 
  that the more precise terms (as listed separately herein) are to be preferred in description.</em></p></dd>  
  
  <hr /><a name="sovereignsbanner"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SOVEREIGN&#39;S BANNER</dt>
  <dd>1) In British Army usage the ceremonial flag (equivalent to a military colour or guidon) 
  of the Royal Military Academy, Sandhurst (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvba.html#banner">banner 6)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc5.html#color">colour 2)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc5.html#colors">colours 2)</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvg6.html#guidon">guidon 2)</a>&rsquo;).</dd>
  <dd>2) In Australian military usage the term given to a special ceremonial flag presented to 
  a military organization by Her Majesty The Queen in place of or in addition to colours 
  (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvba.html#banner">banner 6)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc5.html#color">colour 2)</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc5.html#colors">colours 2)</a>&rsquo;).</dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="sovereignsflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SOVEREIGN&#39;S COLOUR (or COLOR)</dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc5.html#colors">colours 2)</a>&rsquo;. 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2325.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2325.gif" alt="[Sovereign's colour]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2326.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2326.gif" alt="[Sovereign's colour]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <br><em><a href="es^guard.html#1704">King&rsquo;s Colour Infantry of the Royal Guard 1704</a>, Spain (fotw);<a href="es^1841.html"> Queen&rsquo;s Colour of the Chasseurs Isabel II c1840</a>, Spain (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="sovereignsstandard"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SOVEREIGN&#39;S STANDARD </dt>
  <dd>1) Specifically in British military usage, that flag carried as a special mark of distinction 
  by the Life Guards and the Blues and Royals - the Household Cavalry (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-u.html#unionstandard">union standard</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs6.html#standard">standard 2)</a>&rsquo;).</dd>
  <dd>2) Generically see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvr6.html#royalstandard">royal standard 1)</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d307.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d307.gif" alt="[Sovereign standard]" border="0" width="113" height="106">
  </a><br />
  <em>Sovereign's Standard of the Blues and Royals, UK 
  (Graham Bartram) </em> </p>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="spanishstyleshield"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SPANISH-STYLE (SPANISH-SHAPED or SPANISH) SHIELD</dt>
  <dd>The alternative terms sometimes used to describe a round-bottomed shield � a Spanish or Spanish-shaped shield (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf8.html#frenchshield">French shield</a>&rsquo;, &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvg2.html#gothicshield">Gothic shield</a>&rsquo; with its following note, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvi6.html#italianshield">Italian shield</a>&rsquo;, &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvr1.html#rectangularshield">rectangular shield</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvr4.html#roundbottomedshield">round-bottomed shield 2)</a>&rsquo;
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs2.html#semicircularshield">semi-circular shield</a>&rsquo;, &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs3.html#shield">shield 2)</a>&rsquo; and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvt4.html#triarchedtriangularshield">triarched triangular shield</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4873.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4873.gif" alt="" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4874.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4874.gif" alt="" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3412.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3412.gif" alt="" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br>
  <em>Arms of <a href="hr-vz-bt.html#coa">Beretinec</a>, Croatia (fotw); 
  National/State Flag of <a href="es.html">Spain</a> (fotw); 
  Arms of <a href="pl-wm-ba.html#)">Bartoszyce</a>, Poland (fotw)</em> 
  </dd>
  
  &nbsp;<hr /><a name="spanishstyle"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SPANISH-STYLE TRIBAND (or SPANISH TRIBAND)</dt>
  <dd>The alternative terms sometimes used for a horizontal triband, either plain or defaced, with 
  vertical proportions of 1-2-1 � a Spanish triband 
  (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-d.html#deface">defaced 1)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvi4.html#internalproportions">internal proportions</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp4.html#plain">plain 2)</a>&rsquo;, &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvt5.html#triband">triband 1)</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-u.html#unequaltriband">unequal triband</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d681.gif">
<img src="../images/v/vxt-d681.gif" alt="Spain" border="0" height="108"/></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4418.gif">
<img src="../images/v/vxt-d4418.gif" alt="French Polynesia" border="0" height="108" /></a>
<a href="../images/v/vxt-d681a.gif">
<img src="../images/v/vxt-d681a.gif" alt="Lebanon" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Civil Flag/Ensign of <a href="es.html">Spain</a> (fotw); 
  Flag of <a href="pf.html">French Polynesia</a> (fotw); 
  National Flag of <a href="lb.html">Lebanon</a> (fotw)</em></dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="specialbattle"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SPECIAL BATTLE EFFICIENCY PENNANT</dt>
  <dd>1) See '<a href="vxt-dvb3.html#battleefficiencypennant">battle efficiency pennant</a>'.<p>
<a href="../images/v/vxt-d3583.gif">
<img src="../images/v/vxt-d3583.gif" alt="special battle efficiency pennant" border="0" width="79" height="108" /></a><br>
  <a href="us^nvawd.html#bats">Special Battle Efficiency Pennant</a>, USN (fotw) </dd>
    
  <hr /><a name="specification"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SPECIFICATION (or SPEC) </dt>
  <dd>1) The detailed description, either by diagram or in writing, of how the design 
  of a flag is constructed  see &lsquo;<a href="#specificationsheet">specification sheet</a>&rsquo; below 
  (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvd2.html#dimensions">dimensions</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp8.html#proportions">proportions</a>&rsquo; and  
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvt6.html#typeflag">type flag</a>&rsquo;).</dd>
  <dd>2) The act of drawing up such design details. </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="specificationsheet"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SPECIFICATION SHEET (or SPEC SHEET)</dt>
  <dd>The detailed visual presentation of how the design of a flag is constructed, usually 
  showing construction lines and figures and often including the source or sources of any 
  such information &ndash; a construction sheet (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-d.html#dejure">de jure</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvd2.html#dimensions">dimensions</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf2.html#flaglaw">flag law</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp8.html#proportions">proportions</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="#specification">specification</a>&rsquo; above and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvt6.html#typeflag">type flag</a>&rsquo;). 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3757.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3757.gif" alt="specification sheet" border="0" height="108" />
  </a><br />
  <em>Specification sheet for the National Flag of <a href="bh.html#coa">Bahrain</a> (fotw)</em></dd>

  <hr /><a name="speculativeflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SPECULATIVE FLAG (SPECULATIVE DESIGN or SPECULATION)</dt>
  <dd>Alternative terms for the image of a flag, or details of a flag&rsquo;s design/use, for which no exact details are 
  known or can be confirmed � a speculative design or speculation - but see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvr1.html#reconstruction">reconstruction</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>  
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2232.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2232.gif" alt="speculative flag" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2230.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2230.gif" alt="speculative flag" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br />
  <em>Speculative Flag of <a href="us-calom.html">Lomita</a>, US (fotw); Speculative Banner of Arms of <a href="mt!g.html">G&#295;awdex</a>, Malta (fotw)&nbsp; </em></dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="speculativevexillology"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SPECULATIVE VEXILLOLOGY</dt>
  <dd>The study of flags as defined in &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs5.html#speculativeflag">speculative flag</a>&rsquo; above.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3542.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3542.gif" alt="speculative flag" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Speculative image of a <a href="gb-enshs.html#1620">Naval Ensign c1620</a>, England (fotw) </em></dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="spiral"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SPIRAL DECORATION</dt>
  <dd>A term for the practice, now increasingly (but not entirely) obsolete, of 
  decorating a flag pole or the staff of a parade flag or military colour with a spiral 
  decoration, usually in the national or livery colours and often accompanied by a cravat 
  (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc5.html#color">colour 2)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc5.html#color">colour 3)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc9.html#cravat">cravat  1)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvl2.html#liverycolors">livery colours</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp1.html#paradeflag">parade flag</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1501.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1501.gif" alt="[example of a spiral decoration]" border="0" width="117" height="178" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1502.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1502.gif" alt="[example of a spiral decoration]" border="0" width="121" height="160" /></a>
  <br />
  <em>State Flag of San Marino (fotw & CS); National Flag of Brazil on a Military Flagpole (fotw & CS)</em></dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="splice"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SPLICE</dt>
  <dd>1) A naval term for the joint in two pieces of line, halyard or cable, and created by 
  weaving the strands into each other (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dve4.html#eyesplice">eye splice</a>&rsquo;).<br />
  2) (v) The act of creating a joint as detailed above.
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="splitflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SPLIT FLAG </dt>
  <dd>An Anglicization of the Scandinavian terms splitflag or splittflag � see &lsquo;<a href="#splittflag">splitflag</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2827.gif" alt="[Denmark naval/state flag - double pointed]" border="0" height="108">&nbsp;  <br />
  <em>Flag of the <a href="is-royal.html#regt">Regent 1941 � 1944</a>, Iceland (fotw) </em></dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="splittflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SPLITFLAG (or SPLITTFLAG)</dt>
  <dd>1) A term that may be officially used to describe the shape of the Danish state flag/naval ensign and of its variants (see also
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-d.html#dannebrog">dannebrog</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvd4.html#doublepointed">double-pointed</a>&rsquo; 
  and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs1.html#scandinaviancross">Scandinavian cross</a>&rsquo;).</dd>
  <dd>2) A term that may also be used in other Scandinavian countries (particularly Norway with the 
  alternative spelling given above) in place of 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvd4.html#doublepointed">double pointed</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs9.html#swallowtail">swallow-tail(ed)</a>&rsquo; or 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs9.html#swallowtail-tongue">swallow tail and tongue</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d120.gif" alt="[Denmark naval/state flag - double pointed]" border="0" height="108">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3167.gif" alt="[Denmark naval/state flag - double pointed]" border="0" height="108">  
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1519.gif" alt="[Denmark naval/state flag - double pointed]" border="0" height="108">  <br />
  <em>The State Flag/Naval Ensign of <a href="dk.html">Denmark</a> (fotw); 
  Flag of <a href="dk-rail.html">Danish railways </a>(fotw); 
  State/War Flag of <a href="no.html">Norway</a> (fotw) </em></dd>

  <hr /><a name="sportingbanner"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SPORTING BANNER</dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvba.html#banner">banner 3)</a>&rsquo;.</dd>
  <hr /><a name="sportssupporterflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SPORT SUPPORTER&#39;S FLAG/PENNANT</dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="#sportsflag">sports flag 2)</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
<a href="../images/v/vxt-d1557.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1557.gif" alt="[Northern Ireland Football Supporters, UK]" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Northern Ireland <a href="gb-ni@f.html">Football Supporters</a>, UK (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="sportsflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SPORTS (or SPORTING) FLAG (or PENNANT)</dt>
  <dd>1) A flag &ndash; often the appropriate national or provincial flag &ndash; bearing 
  (or defaced with) the name of a sporting club or related slogan &ndash; but see the note below (also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc2.html#carflag">car flag 2)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-d.html#deface">defaced</a>&rsquo; 
  and &lsquo;<a href="#souvenirflags">souvenir flag 1)</a>&rsquo;).</dd>
  <dd>2) A flag or pennant, usually in the club or school colours, bearing an emblem (and often associated lettering) that 
  represents a sporting club or school team&nbsp; &ndash; a sport supporter&#39;s or 
  supporters flag/pennant or a fan&#39;s flag/pennant (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc2.html#carflag">car flag 2)</a>&rsquo;, &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvi4.html#institutionalflagofficial">institutional flags/pennants</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="#souvenirflags">souvenir flag</a>&rsquo;).</dd>
  <dd>3) The flag of a national or international sporting organization (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvi4.html#internationalflag">international flag(s) 2)</a>&rsquo;).</dd>
  <dd>4) One of a varied number of flags that are used to regulate or to assist 
  in running a sporting activity &ndash; for example, the chequered flag in motor racing.
  <p>
<a href="../images/v/vxt-d588.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d588.gif" alt="[Liverpool Football Club]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3734.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3734.gif" alt="[Football Federation of Chile ]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4636.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4636.gif" alt="[Football Association Norway]" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Fan's Flag Liverpool Football Club, UK (CS); 
  Football Federation of <a href="cl@ffc.html">Chile</a> (fotw); 
  <a href="no@.html#nff">Football Association of Norway</a> (fotw) <p>Please note with regard to 1) that in some countries the practice of defacing a 
  national or sub-national flag as described above is either discouraged or is illegal, but continues to be 
  employed by sports fans regardless.</em><hr /><a name="spuriousflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SPURIOUS FLAG</dt>
  <dd>See '<a href="vxt-dvf1.html#fictitiousflag">fictitious flag</a>'.</dd>
  <dd>
  <p><a href="../images/v/vxt-d3075.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3075.gif" alt="[fictitious flag]" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Spurious Flag of French Morocco from the film <a href="ma_fr.html#cblanca">Casablanca</a> (fotw)</em>
  
  <hr /><a name="spurrowel"></a></dd>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SPUR ROWEL (or SPUR WHEEL)</dt>
  <dd>In heraldry see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvr4.html#rowel">rowel</a>&rsquo;. 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3873.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3873.gif" alt="[Spur rowel]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
